[
    {
        "content": "<p>Thanks to a nudge from <span class=\"user-mention\" data-user-id=\"276048\">@Mike Stay</span> I've decided to release the work Greg Egan, John Huerta and I did on the exceptional Jordan algebra as a strange sort of 'spacetime'.   This ties into the connections between the exceptional Jordan algebra and the Standard Model in mysterious ways, so I'm doing it here:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"https://golem.ph.utexas.edu/category/2020/10/octonions_and_the_standard_mod_4.html\">Octonions and the Standard Model (part 5)</a>, <em>The n-Category Cafe</em>.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>But there's a lot of background required, so I've decided to go slow to make it comprehensible.   This time I'm talking about a paper John and I wrote on division algebras and physics in dimensions 3, 4, 6 and 10.   It's fun stuff - I kind of miss working on this sort of thing.</p>",
        "id": 214983734,
        "sender_full_name": "John Baez",
        "timestamp": 1603985603
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>OK, so this seems like it was just the warm-up. Do you anticipate getting to the new stuff in the next post, or is there a bit to go through before then? Just curious, I'm interested to see the new work!</p>",
        "id": 215173684,
        "sender_full_name": "David Michael Roberts",
        "timestamp": 1604118571
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I'm not sure how long it will take to get to the new stuff.   In the next post I want to at least describe the determinant on <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><msub><mi mathvariant=\"fraktur\">h</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"double-struck\">O</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathfrak{h}_3(\\mathbb{O})</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathfrak\">h</span></span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t vlist-t2\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.30110799999999993em;\"><span style=\"top:-2.5500000000000003em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\">3</span></span></span></span><span class=\"vlist-s\">​</span></span><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.15em;\"><span></span></span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathbb\">O</span></span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span></span></span></span> in terms of <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">S</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">p</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">i</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">n</mi></mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mn>9</mn><mo separator=\"true\">,</mo><mn>1</mn><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathrm{Spin}(9,1)</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathrm\">S</span><span class=\"mord mathrm\">p</span><span class=\"mord mathrm\">i</span><span class=\"mord mathrm\">n</span></span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord\">9</span><span class=\"mpunct\">,</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.16666666666666666em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">1</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span></span></span></span>-equivariant operations on scalars, vectors and spinors Minkowski spacetime.  This will show <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">S</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">p</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">i</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">n</mi></mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mn>9</mn><mo separator=\"true\">,</mo><mn>1</mn><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo><mo>⊆</mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">E</mi><mn>6</mn></msub></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathrm{Spin}(9,1) \\subseteq \\mathrm{E}_6</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathrm\">S</span><span class=\"mord mathrm\">p</span><span class=\"mord mathrm\">i</span><span class=\"mord mathrm\">n</span></span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord\">9</span><span class=\"mpunct\">,</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.16666666666666666em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">1</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">⊆</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.83333em;vertical-align:-0.15em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathrm\">E</span></span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t vlist-t2\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.30110799999999993em;\"><span style=\"top:-2.5500000000000003em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\">6</span></span></span></span><span class=\"vlist-s\">​</span></span><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.15em;\"><span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span>, where <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">E</mi><mn>6</mn></msub></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathrm{E}_6</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.83333em;vertical-align:-0.15em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathrm\">E</span></span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t vlist-t2\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.30110799999999993em;\"><span style=\"top:-2.5500000000000003em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\">6</span></span></span></span><span class=\"vlist-s\">​</span></span><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.15em;\"><span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span> (a certain noncompact real form of it) can be defined as the determinant-preserving linear transformations of <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><msub><mi mathvariant=\"fraktur\">h</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"double-struck\">O</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathfrak{h}_3(\\mathbb{O})</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathfrak\">h</span></span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t vlist-t2\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.30110799999999993em;\"><span style=\"top:-2.5500000000000003em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\">3</span></span></span></span><span class=\"vlist-s\">​</span></span><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.15em;\"><span></span></span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathbb\">O</span></span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span></span></span></span>.</p>",
        "id": 215174363,
        "sender_full_name": "John Baez",
        "timestamp": 1604119888
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>This is not new stuff, but it's nice and it's necessary for anything further.</p>",
        "id": 215174430,
        "sender_full_name": "John Baez",
        "timestamp": 1604120038
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>One further step, maybe a bit of a digression but really nice, is a complete description of <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">E</mi><mn>6</mn></msub></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathrm{E}_6</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.83333em;vertical-align:-0.15em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathrm\">E</span></span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t vlist-t2\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.30110799999999993em;\"><span style=\"top:-2.5500000000000003em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\">6</span></span></span></span><span class=\"vlist-s\">​</span></span><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.15em;\"><span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span> in terms of <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">S</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">p</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">i</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">n</mi></mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mn>9</mn><mo separator=\"true\">,</mo><mn>1</mn><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathrm{Spin}(9,1)</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathrm\">S</span><span class=\"mord mathrm\">p</span><span class=\"mord mathrm\">i</span><span class=\"mord mathrm\">n</span></span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord\">9</span><span class=\"mpunct\">,</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.16666666666666666em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">1</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span></span></span></span>, left-handed and right-handed spinors, and scalars:</p>\n<p><span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mn>78</mn><mo>=</mo><mn>45</mn><mo>+</mo><mn>16</mn><mo>+</mo><mn>16</mn><mo>+</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">78 = 45 + 16 + 16 + 1</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.64444em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">7</span><span class=\"mord\">8</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">=</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.72777em;vertical-align:-0.08333em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">4</span><span class=\"mord\">5</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222222222222222em;\"></span><span class=\"mbin\">+</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222222222222222em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.72777em;vertical-align:-0.08333em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">1</span><span class=\"mord\">6</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222222222222222em;\"></span><span class=\"mbin\">+</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222222222222222em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.72777em;vertical-align:-0.08333em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">1</span><span class=\"mord\">6</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222222222222222em;\"></span><span class=\"mbin\">+</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222222222222222em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.64444em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">1</span></span></span></span></p>",
        "id": 215174481,
        "sender_full_name": "John Baez",
        "timestamp": 1604120153
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>It's a bit hard for me to know what's essential and what's just fun.  One possible goal is efficiently proving Dubois-Violette and Todorov's way of getting the Standard Model gauge group from the exceptional Jordan algebra.  Another is explaining what Greg Egan, John Huerta and I did to understand the exceptional Jordan algebra as a kind of \"spacetime\".   In my dreams these would fit together nicely but they don't yet.  Maybe I'll get some ideas as I write.</p>",
        "id": 215174676,
        "sender_full_name": "John Baez",
        "timestamp": 1604120468
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I'm all for seeing the new stuff, but an efficient proof of the SM gauge group result would be good too, of course :-)</p>",
        "id": 215218249,
        "sender_full_name": "David Michael Roberts",
        "timestamp": 1604189664
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I will wind up doing everything, I think.  I realize I need to get this stuff written up to feel happy.   Then maybe I can turn it into an expository paper someday.</p>",
        "id": 215222094,
        "sender_full_name": "John Baez",
        "timestamp": 1604196856
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>One of the most interesting functions on the exceptional Jordan algebra is the determinant. The linear transformations that preserve this form the exceptional Lie group <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">E</mi><mn>6</mn></msub></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathrm{E}_6</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.83333em;vertical-align:-0.15em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathrm\">E</span></span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t vlist-t2\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.30110799999999993em;\"><span style=\"top:-2.5500000000000003em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\">6</span></span></span></span><span class=\"vlist-s\">​</span></span><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.15em;\"><span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span>.   I just wrote a blog article explaining how to compute this determinant in terms of 10-dimensional spacetime geometry: that is, scalars, vectors and spinors in 10d Minkowski spacetime. </p>\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"https://golem.ph.utexas.edu/category/2020/11/octonions_and_the_standard_mod_5.html\">Octonions and the Standard Model (part 6)</a>.</li>\n</ul>",
        "id": 215278594,
        "sender_full_name": "John Baez",
        "timestamp": 1604291329
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Yesterday I goofed off and wrote a blog article about how to describe the exceptional group <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">E</mi><mn>6</mn></msub></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathrm{E}_6</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.83333em;vertical-align:-0.15em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathrm\">E</span></span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t vlist-t2\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.30110799999999993em;\"><span style=\"top:-2.5500000000000003em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\">6</span></span></span></span><span class=\"vlist-s\">​</span></span><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.15em;\"><span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span> using scalars, vectors and spinors in 10d Minkowski spacetime:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"https://golem.ph.utexas.edu/category/2020/11/octonions_and_the_standard_mod_6.html\">Octonions and the Standard Model (part 7)</a>.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>This is work Greg Egan, John Huerta and I did back in November 2015.  I was trying to \"go for broke\" and use this math to cook up a theory of everything.  I stalled out, but we came up with a lot of good math.   Greg Egan used Mathematica to do lots of calculations with octonions, and he came up with the formulas in this post.</p>",
        "id": 215960095,
        "sender_full_name": "John Baez",
        "timestamp": 1604763415
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I just wrote another article in my series:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"https://golem.ph.utexas.edu/category/2020/11/octonions_and_the_standard_mod_7.html\">Octonions and the Standard Model (part 8)</a>.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>This starts giving a geometrical explanation of <em>why</em> we can describe the symmetry group <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">E</mi><mn>6</mn></msub></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathrm{E}_6</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.83333em;vertical-align:-0.15em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathrm\">E</span></span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t vlist-t2\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.30110799999999993em;\"><span style=\"top:-2.5500000000000003em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\">6</span></span></span></span><span class=\"vlist-s\">​</span></span><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.15em;\"><span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span> of the exceptional Jordan algebra in terms of 10d Minkowski spacetime.   It involves the octonionic projective plane <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"double-struck\">O</mi><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">P</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathbb{O}\\mathrm{P}^2</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.9807779999999999em;vertical-align:-0.16667em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathbb\">O</span></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathrm\">P</span></span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.8141079999999999em;\"><span style=\"top:-3.063em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\">2</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span>, so as a warmup I look at the complex projective line <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"double-struck\">C</mi><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">P</mi><mn>1</mn></msup></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathbb{C}\\mathrm{P}^1</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8141079999999999em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathbb\">C</span></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathrm\">P</span></span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.8141079999999999em;\"><span style=\"top:-3.063em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\">1</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span>, which is isomorphic to the 'heavenly sphere': the starry sky you'd see all around you if you were floating in space.</p>\n<p><span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">E</mi><mn>6</mn></msub></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathrm{E}_6</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.83333em;vertical-align:-0.15em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathrm\">E</span></span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t vlist-t2\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.30110799999999993em;\"><span style=\"top:-2.5500000000000003em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\">6</span></span></span></span><span class=\"vlist-s\">​</span></span><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.15em;\"><span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span> acts on <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"double-struck\">O</mi><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">P</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathbb{O}\\mathrm{P}^2</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.9807779999999999em;vertical-align:-0.16667em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathbb\">O</span></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathrm\">P</span></span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.8141079999999999em;\"><span style=\"top:-3.063em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\">2</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span> much as the Lorentz group acts on the heavenly sphere.</p>",
        "id": 216292489,
        "sender_full_name": "John Baez",
        "timestamp": 1605053394
    }
]